SIMPLE: evening
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Evening
<hw>E"ven*ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>⟦aemac⟧fnung</ets>. See <er>even</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Eve</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The latter part and close of the
day, and the beginning of darkness or night; properly, the decline of
the day, or of the sun.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the ascending scale⟦br⟧
Of heaven, the stars that usher <qex>evening</qex> rose.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Sometimes, especially in the Southern parts of the
United States, the afternoon is called <xex>evening</xex>.</note>
<rj><au>Bartlett.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The latter portion, as of life; the declining
period, as of strength or glory.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Sometimes used adjectively; as, <xex>evening</xex> gun.
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Evening</xex> Prayer.⟦rdquo⟧</note>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Evening flower</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a genus
of iridaceous plants (<gen>Hesperantha</gen>) from the Cape of Good
Hope, with sword-shaped leaves, and sweet-scented flowers which expand
in the evening.</cd> -- <col><b>Evening grosbeak</b></col>
<fld>(Zo⟦oum⟧l.)</fld>, <cd>an American singing bird
(<spn>Coccothraustes vespertina</spn>) having a very large bill. Its
color is olivaceous, with the crown, wings, and tail black, and the
under tail coverts yellow. So called because it sings in the
evening.</cd> -- <col><b>Evening primrose</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Primrose</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>The evening star</b></col>, <cd>the
bright star of early evening in the western sky, soon passing below the
horizon; specifically, the planet Venus; -- called also
<altname>Vesper</altname> and <altname>Hesperus</altname>. During
portions of the year, Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn are also evening stars.
See <er>Morning Star</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>evening bag</ent>⟦br⟧
